<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-581-215  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 581 215.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommuting Review: the Gordon Report  May 1 1989 v6 n5 p2(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>National group lobbies for spread of fiber-to-the-home. (Opt inAmerica) (Legal and Regulatory News)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Opt in America is a nonprofit organization, formed in 1988, thatwants to make benefits of the Information Age available to allAmericans by encouraging distribution of fiber-optic cabling intohomes.andP;  Opt in America wants 'a two-way video and datacommunications system that is affordable and available to everyAmerican.' According to Opt in America, fiber's transmissioncapacity means that more in-home education, entertainment,banking, and work, as well as local or even national two-waydiscussions, are possible.andP;  To make these ideas real, regulatoryreforms are needed so that telephone companies and other serviceproviders can distribute information and services.andP;  Opt in Americamember Milton Benjamin, responsible for ongoing coordination, saysthat it is time to decide what kind of a society we want in theInformation Age and what kind of public policy is needed to getthere.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsGovernment RegulationInformation ServicesTelephone CompaniesTelecommunicationsSocial IssuesIssues-SocietyOpt in AmericaUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionUnited StatesNonprofit OrganizationDeregulation.andO;Person:    Benjamin, Milton (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>